<h2>The HIRDLS Class 100 Cleanroom</title></h2>

<p>Computational fluid dynamics was used to model the
cleanroom components to minimise the degree of air turbulence created
by vortex shedding from bulky components, such as the <a
href="chamber_1.html">thermal vacuum chamber</a>. The final cross-flow
cleanroom design is shown schematically Fig 1.</p>

<p>The <strong>mobile tunnel structure</strong>, Fig 2, shown in front of the
<strong>auxiliary filter bank</strong>, provides a better than <strong>Class 100
holding area (typically Class 10, 0.5 micron particles)</strong> for space
instrumention, while the side wall nearest the chamber ensures that
turbulence created by the chamber is continuously dissipated. In
addition to high levels of particulate filtration, both the make-up
air and the return air streams are passed through <strong>activated carbon
filters</strong> to maintain molecular contamination at low levels within
the clean areas.</p>

<p>Services are routed to the chamber via spacious, enclosed floor
ducts, while the <a href="mass_3.html">seismic mass</a> is
accommodated in a large service pit located directly under the vacuum
chamber.</p>

